Appendix B: Emblems and Flags -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIf memory was simply about past events, public authorities would never put their ever-shrinking budgets at its service. Rather, memory is actually about the present moment, as Pierre Nora puts it: “Through the past, we venerate above all ourselves.” This book examines how collective memory and material culture are used to support present political and ideological needs in contemporary society. Using the memorialization of the Troubles in contemporary Northern Ireland as a case study, this book investigates how non-state, often proscribed, organizations have filled a societal vacuum in the creation of public memorials. In particular, these groups have sifted through the past to propose “official” collective narratives of national identification, historical legitimation, and moral justifications for violence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aCollective memoryxNorthern Ireland. 0aCollective memoryzNorthern Ireland. 0aMemorializationxPolitical aspectsxNorthern Ireland. 0aMemorializationxPolitical aspectszNorthern Ireland. 0aPolitical violencexHistoryx20th centuryxNorthern Ireland. 0aPolitical violencezNorthern IrelandxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aDonnan, Hastings, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311099823840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178238408340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782384083423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782384083/original  a978-3-11-099823-8  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014